In the context of email, "cc" stands for "carbon copy," while "bcc" stands for "blind carbon copy." Both of these terms refer to the way that a message can be sent to multiple recipients.

When you include someone's email address as a "cc" recipient on a message, the person will receive a copy of the message along with the main recipients. This means that the other recipients will be able to see the cc'd person's email address in the list of recipients.

On the other hand, when you include someone's email address as a "bcc" recipient on a message, the person will receive the message, but their email address will not be visible to the other recipients. This can be useful if you are sending a group message to many people and don't want the recipients to be aware of the full list of recipients.

In general, it's considered good email etiquette to use "bcc" only when necessary, and to use "cc" for all but the most sensitive messages. This allows recipients to see who else is receiving the message, which can be helpful for organizing follow-up actions or for maintaining a record of who was cc'd on a message.
